1 Section 1. Chapter 178 of NRS is hereby amended by adding
2 thereto a new section to read as follows:
3 1. If the treating psychiatrist of a defendant determines that
4 psychiatric medication is necessary to restore the defendant to
5 competency and the defendant refuses to take such medication
6 voluntarily, the Administrator or the Administrator’s designee
7 shall:
8 (a) Submit a written report to this effect to the committing
9 court; and
10 (b) Send a copy of the written report to the prosecuting
11 attorney and the counsel for the defendant.
12 2. Upon receiving a copy of the written report submitted
13 pursuant to subsection 1, the prosecuting attorney may file a
14 motion with the court requesting a hearing to determine whether
15 the court should issue an order authorizing the involuntary
16 administration of psychiatric medication to the defendant for the
17 purpose of treatment to competency.
18 3. Upon the filing of a motion pursuant to subsection 2, the
19 court shall schedule a hearing on the motion. The hearing must be
20 held within 10 days after the filing of the motion.
21 4. After the hearing described in subsection 3, the court may
22 issue an order authorizing the involuntary administration of
23 psychiatric medication to the defendant if, after considering the
24 facts and circumstances of the case, the court finds that:
25 (a) The State has an important governmental interest in
26 bringing the defendant to trial;
27 (b) Administering the psychiatric medication to the defendant
28 is substantially likely to render the defendant competent to stand
29 trial;
30 (c) Any alternative, less intrusive treatment is unlikely to
31 achieve substantially the same result; and
